For anyone facing this issue all you need to do is instead of returning an object return a string. Using an XmlMapper, which is a subclass of ObjectMapper, create a string and return it. However, the object which will be converted into a string needs to have the same configs as the employee object in the case above.
How to do it.

step 1: Get the required dependency for the XmlMapper class.
```
&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;com.fasterxml.jackson.dataformat&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;jackson-dataformat-xml&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    &lt;version&gt;2.11.1&lt;/version&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;
```
step 2: Inside the method that you intend to return xmls with create an XmlMapper object.
```
XmlMapper xmlMapper = new XmlMapper();
```
step 3: Now convert the object that you intend to return as an xml into a string using the xmlMapper object created above. In the example provided above, the object to return was employee hence el has been used here.
```
String xml = xmlMapper.writeValueAsString(el);
```
Step 4: return the string
```
return xml;
```
NB: your method or controller will have to return a String and not an Employee object in this case. Additionally, use `@Produces(MediaType.APPLICATION_XML)` above your resource to signal to your consumer what to expect.

Also, in your consumers&#39; header, it is good but not necessary to show what you are expecting from the server by using a `Accept: Application/xml` in your headers. It is not necessary since most consumers by default accept all data formats.

